### ============================================================================
### service-policy — PERMISSION ENUMERATION walkthrough (ADR-030)
###   GET /v1/apps/{app}/permissions    the pairs the caller can act on
###
### Open in VS Code (REST Client) or IntelliJ HTTP Client; run top-down.
### Start the app first:  ./mvnw quarkus:dev    (Docker running for MongoDB + OIDC)
###
### WHAT THIS IS
###   For every (resourceType, action) in the app's catalogue (ADR-028), the engine
###   evaluates the active policies WITH NO RESOURCE INSTANCE, three-valued, and returns
###   the pairs the subject can act on. It is what a UI calls once per session to render
###   menus, sections and "New" buttons without a call per button.
###
### ⚠️ ADVISORY, NEVER ENFORCEMENT (ADR-030 §2)
###   The response is a HINT FOR RENDERING, not an authorization decision. A UI that
###   hides a button it should have shown is a usability bug; a backend that SKIPS
###   /evaluate because /permissions said yes is a SECURITY BUG. Always enforce each
###   real action with /evaluate, using resource attributes the backend trusts.
###
### THE THREE OUTCOMES
###   deterministic permit  → listed, "conditional": false   (no instance changes it)
###   depends on instance   → listed, "conditional": true    (+ dependsOn)
###   deterministic deny    → OMITTED                         (no instance changes it)
###   Omitting the conditional case would hide controls the user can in fact use for some
###   resources — a silent false negative. Marking it is the point of the design.
###
### TWO PATHS FOR THE CLIENT
###   type-level questions (is the button ever usable?) → THIS endpoint, one call.
###   instance-level questions (may I edit THIS row?)   → /evaluate per instance, with
###   resource attributes picked by dependsOn:  attributes: pick(row, entry.dependsOn)
###
### Subject is the caller's own JWT sub (self only, ADR-013). No body, no query params.
### Depends on the app's catalogue (ADR-028) and, for claim-derived subject attributes,
### its configuration (ADR-029). Without them the answer degrades honestly (see step 5).
### ============================================================================

@host = http://localhost:8080
@auth = Bearer {{jwt}}
@auth_admin = Bearer {{admin_jwt}}


### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### SETUP (admin) — a catalogue, a config, and policies on the four outcomes
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 0a) Declare the vocabulary of "document" (ADR-028). Without a catalogue there is
###     nothing to enumerate and the answer is an empty list.
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/action-catalogue
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{ "resourceType": "document", "actions": ["create", "read", "update", "delete"] }


### 0b) Map a subject attribute from a token claim (ADR-029), so a type-level policy can
###     read it. Here subject.attr.area comes from the token's "dept" claim.
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/configuration
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{ "subjectAttributes": { "area": "dept" } }


### 0c) create — type-level PERMIT (reads only subject + resource type): DETERMINISTIC.
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{ "policyId": "doc-create", "version": 1, "resourceType": "document", "actions": ["create"],
  "combiningAlgorithm": "DENY_OVERRIDES", "defaultEffect": "DENY",
  "rules": [ { "id": "by-area", "effect": "PERMIT",
    "condition": { "type": "comparison", "op": "EQ",
      "left": {"ref": "subject.attr.area"}, "right": {"value": "north"} } } ] }

### …then activate it (GET it for the ETag, then POST /activate If-Match: "0"). Repeat
### 0c-style creation + activation for the two policies below.


### 0d) update — reads a RESOURCE attribute: INDETERMINATE without the instance.
###     doc-update PERMITs when resource.attr.areaId == subject.attr.area. The areaId is
###     unknown here, so the pair is conditional and dependsOn = ["areaId"].
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{ "policyId": "doc-update", "version": 1, "resourceType": "document", "actions": ["update"],
  "combiningAlgorithm": "DENY_OVERRIDES", "defaultEffect": "DENY",
  "rules": [ { "id": "area-scope", "effect": "PERMIT",
    "condition": { "type": "comparison", "op": "EQ",
      "left": {"ref": "resource.attr.areaId"}, "right": {"ref": "subject.attr.area"} } } ] }


### 0e) delete — a policy that DENIES deterministically → the pair is OMITTED.
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/policies
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{ "policyId": "doc-delete-block", "version": 1, "resourceType": "document", "actions": ["delete"],
  "combiningAlgorithm": "DENY_OVERRIDES", "defaultEffect": "DENY",
  "rules": [ { "id": "never", "effect": "DENY",
    "condition": { "type": "comparison", "op": "EQ", "left": {"value": 1}, "right": {"value": 1} } } ] }

### (read has NO policy → also omitted, by the fail-safe default.)
### Activate doc-create, doc-update and doc-delete-block before the GET below.


### ============================================================================
### 1) ENUMERATE — the three outcomes in one response
### ============================================================================
### Use a token whose "dept" claim is "north" so subject.attr.area resolves.
GET {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/permissions
Authorization: {{auth}}

### EXPECTED  200 OK
### Headers:  ETag: "<hex>"   Cache-Control: private, max-age=30
### {
###   "app": "rh",
###   "subject": "<sub-from-jwt>",
###   "permissions": [
###     { "resourceType": "document", "action": "create", "conditional": false },
###     { "resourceType": "document", "action": "update", "conditional": true,
###       "dependsOn": ["areaId"] }
###   ],
###   "generatedAt": "2026-07-23T…Z"
### }
### Entries sorted by (resourceType, action). NOTE what is ABSENT:
###   - "delete" — a deterministic deny (doc-delete-block), omitted.
###   - "read"   — no applicable policy, omitted (fail-safe default).
### "create" is unconditional (type-level). "update" is conditional and TELLS THE CLIENT
### which resource attribute to send: dependsOn = ["areaId"]. `dependsOn` is present only
### on conditional pairs — an unconditional entry has no such key.


### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### 2) HONOUR THE dependsOn — the instance-level second call
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### For the conditional "update" pair, ask per instance with exactly the attributes
### dependsOn named — pick(row, ["areaId"]) from the row the UI is rendering.
POST {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/evaluate
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{ "action": "document:update",
  "resource": { "type": "document", "id": "d1", "attributes": { "areaId": "north" } } }

### EXPECTED  200 OK → allowed: true   (areaId matches the subject's area)
### This is enforcement. A policy change from areaId to ownerId updates dependsOn on the
### next /permissions call, and this generic client adapts with no code change.


### ============================================================================
### 3) CACHING — revalidate with If-None-Match → 304
### ============================================================================
### The response carries a strong ETag over the COMPUTED RESULT (not a policy version:
### a subject-attribute change must invalidate it too). Send it back to revalidate.
GET {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/permissions
Authorization: {{auth}}
If-None-Match: "<paste the ETag from step 1>"

### EXPECTED  304 Not Modified, same ETag, no body — when nothing changed.
### A short server-side TTL (30s) bounds staleness; within it a policy or attribute
### change may not be reflected yet. That is acceptable: the answer is advisory and
### enforcement re-checks. Push invalidation is a deliberate v2 (ADR-030 §5).


### ============================================================================
### 4) SELF ONLY
### ============================================================================
### There is no way to ask for another subject's permissions here — no query param, no
### body. That is a different question (an admin screen listing what someone else can do)
### with a different authorization model, and it belongs to its own endpoint (ADR-030 §1).

### 4a) 401 — no token
GET {{host}}/v1/apps/rh/permissions

### EXPECTED  401 (OIDC challenge, no problem+json body)


### ============================================================================
### 5) DEGRADATION — honest, never widening
### ============================================================================
### 5a) An app with NO catalogue → nothing to enumerate → empty list, still 200 + ETag.
GET {{host}}/v1/apps/no-catalogue-app/permissions
Authorization: {{auth}}

### EXPECTED  200 OK → { …, "permissions": [], … }

### 5b) No configuration / no claim mapping → the engine cannot derive subject attributes,
###     so a policy reading subject.attr.* is INDETERMINATE and its pair comes back
###     conditional rather than deterministic. Fewer resolvable attributes make MORE pairs
###     conditional — never more permitted (ADR-030 §Consequences, ADR-011). A conditional
###     pair whose indeterminacy is a SUBJECT attribute carries no dependsOn: the client
###     never supplies subject attributes, so it is never asked for them.


### ============================================================================
### HOW TO OBTAIN TOKENS (dev)
### ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
### In quarkus:dev the OIDC dev services start a Keycloak. Get tokens via the Dev UI
### (http://localhost:8080/q/dev) → OIDC. For step 1, the {{jwt}} token needs a "dept"
### claim of "north" for subject.attr.area to resolve (add a protocol mapper, or map a
### claim your realm already issues in the app's configuration at step 0b).
###
### RELATED FILES:
###   action-catalogue.http        the (resourceType, action) vocabulary (ADR-028)
###   app-configuration.http       claim mapping and attribute source (ADR-029)
###   evaluation-endpoints.http    /evaluate, /evaluate/batch — the enforcement path
### ============================================================================
